\begin_layout Subsection
What is a gravitational wave
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A gravitational wave is a solution to Einstein's equation in the weak field
 limit
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Do we need the weak field limit? In this limit the waves are harmonic, are
 there 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

non-linear waves
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the full theory?
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Gravitational waves are 
\series bold
transverse traceless waves traveling at the speed of light
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Transverse: We all know what it means, the same as an electromagnetic field.
 The perturbation that the wave produces is transverse with its direction
 of propagation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Traceless: The waves have equal and opposite effects in two perpendicular
 directions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A wave traveling in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR z$
\end_inset

 direction produces relative motion in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR y$
\end_inset

 directions of free masses.
 The motion in 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR y$
\end_inset

 is identical (thus traceless waves).
 This are physical motions that can e.g.
 stretch a spring.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A gravitational wave traveling through flat space has a metric 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{\mu\nu}=\eta_{\mu\nu}+h_{\mu\nu}\label{Equation: metric with perturbation from a wave}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is the Minkowski metric and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 a small perturbation.
 If the wave travels in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR z$
\end_inset

 direction then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{\mu\nu}\sim\SQBRACKETS{\begin{matrix}0\\
 & a & b\\
 & b & -a\\
 &  &  & 0
\end{matrix}}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 represent the two possible polarizations of the wave.
 I.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h=ah_{+}+bh_{\times}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{+}\sim\SQBRACKETS{\begin{matrix}0\\
 & 1\\
 &  & -1\\
 &  &  & 0
\end{matrix}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\times}\sim\SQBRACKETS{\begin{matrix}0\\
 & 0 & 1\\
 & 1 & 0\\
 &  &  & 0
\end{matrix}}$
\end_inset

 are the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

basis tensors
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 representing each polarization, called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

plus
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cross
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 respectively.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Figure: polarization of a gravitational wave"

\end_inset

 the two polarization modes are represented graphically.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
htmltag{tag_name=image}{src=https://i.stack.imgur.com/IW50W.png}{style=max-width:
 100
\backslash
%; width: 444px;}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Polarization modes of a gravitational wave.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Figure: polarization of a gravitational wave"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Detection of gravitational waves with Michelson interferometer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Michelson interferometer"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michelson_interferometer"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (like the one used to prove that there was no ether) is ideal to detect
 changes in length in two orthogonal directions.
 It compares the time it takes light to travel each of the two arms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For light we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\DIFERENTIAL s^{2}=0\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

 From general relativity we also have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\DIFERENTIAL s^{2}=g_{\mu\nu}\DIFERENTIAL x^{\mu}\DIFERENTIAL x^{\nu}\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

 Let's consider the Michelson interferometer aligned with its arms in the
 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR y$
\end_inset

 direction.
 If we look what happens to the light only in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR x$
\end_inset

 direction then 
\begin_inset Formula $\DIFERENTIAL x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\ne0$
\end_inset

 only for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=1$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=g_{11}\DIFERENTIAL x\DIFERENTIAL x\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

 Replacing 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Equation: metric with perturbation from a wave"

\end_inset

 this is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=-c^{2}\DIFERENTIAL t^{2}+\PARENTHESES{1+h_{11}\PARENTHESES{\omega t-\VECTOR k\cdot\VECTOR x}}\DIFERENTIAL x^{2}\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

This can be seen as a modulation to the distance
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Can it also be seen as a modulation to the speed of light? I mean: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\DIFERENTIAL x}{\DIFERENTIAL t}=\frac{c}{\sqrt{1+h_{11}\PARENTHESES{\omega t-\VECTOR k\cdot\VECTOR x}}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We can integrate 
\begin_inset Formula $\DIFERENTIAL t$
\end_inset

 to see how much time it takes light to travel some distance: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\intop_{0}^{\tau_{\text{out}}}\DIFERENTIAL t & =\frac{1}{c}\intop_{0}^{L}\sqrt{1+h_{11}}\DIFERENTIAL x\\
 & \approx\frac{1}{c}\intop_{0}^{L}\PARENTHESES{1+\frac{1}{2}h_{11}\PARENTHESES{\omega t-\VECTOR k\cdot\VECTOR x}+\dots}\DIFERENTIAL x
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 where in the second line 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{1+x}\approx1+\frac{x}{2}+\dots$
\end_inset

.
 This is the time it takes light to travel from 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 to the end of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR x$
\end_inset

 arm at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=L$
\end_inset

.
 There, there is a mirror so it bounces back so we have the same expression
 repeated.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau_{0\to L\to0}=\frac{2L}{c}+\frac{1}{2c}\intop_{0}^{L}h_{11}\PARENTHESES{\omega t-\VECTOR k\cdot\VECTOR x}\DIFERENTIAL x\text{.}\label{Equation: tau 0 L 0 in x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the interferometer we are interested in the difference in time it takes
 light to travel each arm, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\tau=\tau_{0\to L\to0}^{\VERSOR x}-\tau_{0\to L\to0}^{\VERSOR y}\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

The expression in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Equation: tau 0 L 0 in x"

\end_inset

 is for light traveling in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR x$
\end_inset

 direction.
 In the 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR y$
\end_inset

 direction it is the same but with 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{22}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{11}$
\end_inset

.
 If we now consider (to make it simple) a wave propagating in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR z$
\end_inset

 direction then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{11}=-h_{22}=h
\]

\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\tau=\frac{1}{c}\intop_{0}^{L}h\PARENTHESES{\omega t-\VECTOR k\cdot\VECTOR x}\DIFERENTIAL x\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

We can also consider the limit 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega\tau_{0\to L\to0}\ll1
\]

\end_inset

which is the same as considering the wavelength of the gravitational wave
 much bigger than the length of the arms of the interferometer or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
kL\ll1\text{. }
\]

\end_inset

 In this limit we can regard 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 as constant along the integration, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\PARENTHESES{\omega t-\VECTOR k\cdot\VECTOR x}\approx h\PARENTHESES{\omega t}
\]

\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\intop_{0}^{L}h\DIFERENTIAL x=hL$
\end_inset

.
 So finally 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta\tau=h\PARENTHESES t\frac{2L}{c}\text{.}\label{Equation: sa7td89gasdoasgyou}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tau$
\end_inset

 is basically the signal that we will measure, so increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 also increases the signal
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 also increases the signal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is true in the 
\begin_inset Formula $L\ll\lambda$
\end_inset

 limit.
 Anyway, for a 
\begin_inset Formula $1\KILO{Hz}$
\end_inset

 signal we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1\KILO{Hz}}\approx300\KILO m$
\end_inset

 so current detectors (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim5\KILO m$
\end_inset

) are still well within that limit.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 That is the reason for making very big interferometers.
 The limiting factor for the size of the current detectors is the money
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Saulson 2013 gravitational wave detection principles and practice"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The freely falling masses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As stated before, a gravitational wave induces a relative movement between
 freely falling masses.
 In the Michelson interferometer these masses should be the beam splitter
 and the mirrors in the end of each arm.
 If these elements are attached to the ground, they are the opposite to
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

freely falling masses
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 If this were the case, when the gravitational wave arrives it will try
 to change the distance between them but the other forces would compensate
 this and they would not move.
 So the mirrors and the beam splitter have to be mounted in some special
 way such that they can be regarded as free masses.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To accomplish this they are suspended like pendulums (sophisticated pendulums).
 In the low angle regime the equation of motion for the pendulum is 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ddot{x}+kx=F_{\text{external}}$
\end_inset

 which in the 
\bar under
frequency domain
\bar default
 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\PARENTHESES{-\frac{m}{k}\omega^{2}+1}x=\frac{1}{k}F_{\text{external}}\text{.}\label{Equation: pendulum in frequency domain}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Note here that for 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\gg\sqrt{\frac{k}{m}}$
\end_inset

 the dominant term is 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ddot{x}$
\end_inset

 so it behaves as a free mass while for 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\ll\sqrt{\frac{k}{m}}$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Formula $kx$
\end_inset

 term dominates and it keeps the mass fixed at a mean position.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Why pendulums and not springs?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Equation: pendulum in frequency domain"

\end_inset

 describes a mass attached to a spring, which is the small angle limit for
 a pendulum.
 Why using pendulums instead of springs? The reason is to reduce noise.
 In the case of the pendulum the 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR x$
\end_inset

 component of the restoring force is a projection of the gravitational force
 exerted by the Earth, which is a conservative force.
 In the case of a spring, it is the mean force resulting after adding all
 the microscopic forces from the particles that make up the spring.
 Thus, it is to be expected that the spring is more noisy.
 More details in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Saulson 2013 gravitational wave detection principles and practice"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The importance of multiple observations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "radiation pattern"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radiation_pattern"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for a gravitational wave detector looks like the one shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Figure: gravitational wave detector radiation pattern"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 It is remarkably isotropic
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Saulson 2013 gravitational wave detection principles and practice"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This makes it impossible to tell where the wave is coming from
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The opposite to this is an optical telescope that has a radiation pattern
 that is almost a Dirac delta pointing in the direction of observation.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Multiple observations are required to tell where an event is coming from
 using the arrival time of the wave to each observatory and the distance
 between them:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Observation at one single point: You cannot tell anything about where the
 wave is coming from.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Observation at two points: It is possible to determine a circumference in
 the sky.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Observation at three points: Determines the intersection of two circles
 so the event is coming from one of two points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Observation at four points: Determines the position unambiguously.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
htmltag{tag_name=image}{src=media/1.svg}{style=max-width: 100
\backslash
%;}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Response of a gravitational wave interferometer as a function of direction,
 averaged over polarizations.
 Image copy-pasted from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Saulson 2013 gravitational wave detection principles and practice"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Figure: gravitational wave detector radiation pattern"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Noise sources
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The signal produced by gravitational waves in gravitational detectors is
 very small, we are talking of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Saulson 2013 gravitational wave detection principles and practice"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta L}{L}\sim10^{-22}\text{.}\label{Equation: DeltaL sobre L que queremos medir}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Thus, it is crucial to understand and mitigate the noise sources.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Shot noise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Michelson interferometer can be seen as a transducer that converts differences
 in length to differences in light power at its output.
 If the wavelength of the light is kept constant (and so the energy of the
 photons) then measuring the power is equivalent to counting the number
 of photons per unit time received.
 These photons follow a Poisson distribution with expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{P_{\text{out}}}{h\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 This introduces a fundamental source of noise with origin in quantum fluctuatio
ns.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{P_{\text{out}}}{h\nu}\ggg1$
\end_inset

 the Poisson distribution can be approximated by a Gaussian with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\sigma^{2}=\frac{P_{\text{out}}}{h\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 In this limit we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\sigma}{\mu}=\sqrt{\frac{h\nu}{P_{\text{out}}}}
\]

\end_inset

 so making 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\text{out}}$
\end_inset

 as large as possible reduces the shot noise.
 There are a number of ways of accomplishing this, by increasing the laser
 power, using a 
\emph on
power recycling technique
\emph default
, etc.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Thermal noise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As every system in the universe, here we also have thermal noise.
 It is indeed one of the strongest noise sources
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Saulson 2013 gravitational wave detection principles and practice"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Thermal noise in a gravitational wave detector is a generalization of the
 
\emph on
Brownian motion
\emph default
.
 Each of the nearly free mirrors can be regarded as a very big Brownian
 particle.
 Air molecules hitting on them would induce small Brownian motion, that
 is why the mirrors are suspended in vacuum.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are still other sources that can induce Brownian motion.
 One of them is related to the materials used to hold the mirrors.
 This explains why mirrors are held with pendulum-like systems: the restoring
 force is the horizontal projection of gravity which, as a conservative
 force, lacks of thermal noise
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Saulson 2013 gravitational wave detection principles and practice"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This makes the thermal noise coming from the holding mechanism negligible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The biggest contribution to thermal noise are the internal degrees of freedom
 of the mirrors.
 Basically there are vibrations that introduce a noise spectrum starting
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $10\KILO{Hz}$
\end_inset

.
 To reduce this source of noise there are basically two options: 1) use
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the best possible material
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the mirrors and 2) lower the temperature.
 Current interferometers use mirrors made of 
\emph on
fused silica
\emph default
 at room temperature.
 Future interferometers are planning to use cryogenic systems instead.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another source of thermal noise is the coating of the mirrors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Seismic noise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is not hard to understand what this means and/or where it comes from.
 When seeking for such small displacements, every vibration that the Earth
 makes is important.
 Apparently, every part of the Earth's surface is continuously shaking with
 amplitudes of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim1\MICRO m$
\end_inset

 on time scales of seconds.
 If we are trying to measure magnitudes as stated in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Equation: DeltaL sobre L que queremos medir"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $L\sim1\KILO m$
\end_inset

, this 
\begin_inset Formula $1\MICRO m$
\end_inset

 shakes are almost infinite.
 There are two possibilities to fight against this noise: 1) somehow isolate
 our system and 2) go deep underground where the seismic noise is smaller.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Current detectors are all at ground level and use sophisticated pendulum
 systems to isolate the seismic noise.
 The best seismic noise attenuator to date (2013) is the one used in the
 Virgo detector, shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Figure: Virgo super attenuator"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

