\begin_layout Subsubsection
Other noises of source
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course there are other sources of noise, in the electronics, in the control
 systems, in the intensity and wavelength of the laser, etc.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
30.09.2021
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gravitational waves arise in the linearized theory.
 The speed of gravity is the same as the speed of light.
 General relativity is highly non linear
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}=-\frac{1}{2}g\COVARIANTINDEX{\nu\nu}R=\frac{8\pi G}{c^{4}}T\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}
\]

\end_inset

 Now we consider a weak field approximation, basically very far away from
 the sources.
 The waves are just perturbations to a time-independent background curvature.
 For this to hold the curvature radius has to be much greater than the wavelengt
h of the gravitational waves
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Does this mean that even on Earth (i.e.
 very far away from sources and in a relatively weak field) there is a regime
 for non linear waves?
\end_layout

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Time independent curvature radius}\gg\text{wavelength}
\]

\end_inset

 In this conditions the metric tensor can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}=\eta\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}+h\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is the Minkowski and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is a small perturbation with 
\begin_inset Formula $\MODULE{h\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}}\ll1$
\end_inset

.
 Because our space is esentialy flat (linearized theory) then it holds 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}=\eta\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu\alpha}\eta\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\nu\beta}h\COVARIANTINDEX{\alpha\beta}
\]

\end_inset

 and so the inverse metric is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}=\eta\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}-h\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

 Now I see 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

trace reversed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and it says 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{h}\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}=h\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}-\frac{1}{2}\eta\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}h
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h=h\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}h\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 I don't know what this is.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a gauge freedom given by the infinitesimal transformation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu}\to x\PRIME\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu}=x\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu}+\xi\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu}\PARENTHESES x
\]

\end_inset

 and this holds if 
\begin_inset Formula $\MODULE{\partial\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu}\xi\COVARIANTINDEX{\nu}}\ll\MODULE{h\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}}$
\end_inset

.
 This transformation modifies 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}\PARENTHESES x\to h\PRIME\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}\PARENTHESES x=h\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}\PARENTHESES x-\PARENTHESES{\partial\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu}\xi\COVARIANTINDEX{\nu}-\partial\COVARIANTINDEX{\nu}\xi\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu}}
\]

\end_inset

Cannot read something in blue, next: 
\begin_inset Formula $\MODULE{h\PRIME\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}}\ll1$
\end_inset

.
 Now we choose the Lorentz (Hilbert) gauge which means 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu,\nu}=0
\]

\end_inset

 and as a result we have (the Einstein equation is this?)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\PARENTHESES{-\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial^{2}t^{2}}+\nabla^{2}}\bar{h}\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}=-16\pi T\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}
\]

\end_inset

 where now we are using 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G=c=1\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

 In vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\square\bar{h}\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}=0
\]

\end_inset

 so this means that we will have plane wave solutions of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{h}\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}=\mathscr{A}e\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}e^{ik\COVARIANTINDEX{\alpha}k\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\alpha}}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 is the amplitude, 
\begin_inset Formula $e\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is the polarization tensor and 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\dots}$
\end_inset

 is an exponential.
 
\begin_inset Formula $k\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is the wave vector which is lightlike, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu}k\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu}=0\GRAY{\leftarrow\text{Lightlike}}
\]

\end_inset

 (because the wave travels at speed 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

).
 The polarization and wave vector are orthogonal, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}k\COVARIANTINDEX{\nu}=0\GRAY{\leftarrow\text{Transverse waves}}
\]

\end_inset

 so this means that the waves are transverse.
 The degrees of freedom are 6 in total, I did not follow the explanation.
 The calculation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
16\text{ components and gauge conditions}\rightarrow10-4=6\text{.}\GRAY{\leftarrow\text{Degrees of freedom}}
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The waves are 
\bar under
transverse and traceless
\bar default
.
 Transverse wave means 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{ij}k\COVARIANTINDEX j=0\GRAY{\leftarrow\text{Transverse waves}}
\]

\end_inset

 and this comes from 
\begin_inset Formula $e\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{0p}=0$
\end_inset

 (?).
 Traceless wave means that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX i\COVARIANTINDEX i=0\GRAY{\leftarrow\text{Traceless waves}}
\]

\end_inset

 and I am not sure where this comes from.
 We can use a transverse and traceless (TT) gauge for the metric and this
 will give us that there are two independent polarizations and trace-reversed
 metric 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{h}\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}=h\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}\text{.}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's now consider a wave propagating in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR z$
\end_inset

 direction.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Wave in the }z\text{ direction}\rightarrow\LBRACE{\begin{aligned} & k\COVARIANTINDEX z=\omega\\
 & k\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX 0=\omega\\
 & k\COVARIANTINDEX x=k\COVARIANTINDEX y=0\\
 & e\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{0\mu}=e\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{z\mu}=0\\
 & e\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{xx}=-e\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{yy}
\end{aligned}
}
\]

\end_inset

 The independent components are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\GRAY{\text{Two independent components}\rightarrow}\LBRACE{\begin{aligned} & e\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{xx}\DEF e^{\oplus}\equiv\text{plus polarization}\\
 & e\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{xy}\DEF e^{\otimes}\equiv\text{cross polarization}
\end{aligned}
}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If now we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $e\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{xy}=0$
\end_inset

 then we only have 
\begin_inset Formula $\oplus$
\end_inset

 polarization, i.e.
 a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pure 
\begin_inset Formula $\oplus$
\end_inset

 metric
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 In this case the line element has the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\DIFERENTIAL s^{2}=-\DIFERENTIAL t^{2}+\PARENTHESES{1+h_{\oplus}}\DIFERENTIAL x^{2}+\PARENTHESES{1-h_{\oplus}}\DIFERENTIAL y^{2}+\DIFERENTIAL z^{2}
\]

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\oplus}=\mathscr{A}e\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{xx}e^{i\omega\PARENTHESES{t-z}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we have a wave with 
\begin_inset Formula $e\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{xx}=0$
\end_inset

 then we have 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pure 
\begin_inset Formula $\otimes$
\end_inset

 polarization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and we have the same but with a 45 degrees rotation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effect of each of these polarizations on a ring of free particles is
 shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Figure: polarization of a gravitational wave"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

