\begin_layout Standard
We can also define a circular polarization basis as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\GRAY{\text{Circular polarization}\rightarrow}\LBRACE{\begin{aligned} & e_{R}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\PARENTHESES{e_{\oplus}+ie_{\otimes}}\\
 & e_{L}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\PARENTHESES{e_{\oplus}-ie_{\otimes}}
\end{aligned}
}
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's look now a the geodesic equation: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\DIFERENTIAL^{2}x\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\alpha}}{\DIFERENTIAL\tau^{2}}+\Gamma_{\mu\nu}^{\alpha}\frac{\DIFERENTIAL x\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu}}{\DIFERENTIAL\tau}\frac{\DIFERENTIAL x\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\nu}}{\DIFERENTIAL\tau}=0\GRAY{\leftarrow\text{Geodesic equation}}
\]

\end_inset

 If we use the TT gauge (see before) this is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\DIFERENTIAL^{2}x\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX i}{\DIFERENTIAL\tau^{2}}=-\Gamma_{00}^{i}=-\frac{1}{2}\PARENTHESES{2h\COVARIANTINDEX{i0,0}-h\COVARIANTINDEX{00,i}}=0
\]

\end_inset

 so this means that the particle is not accelerated.
 This means that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the TT gauge defines a coordinate system that is co-moving with freely falling
 test particles
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This means following the motion induced by the wave?
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
TT time is the proper time on a clock of a freely falling test particle
 (
\begin_inset Formula $h\COVARIANTINDEX{0\mu}=0$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we look at the equation of geodesic deviation, which (I believe) means
 how the separation of neighboring particles changes, i.e.
 it somehow means the tidal forces.
 This equation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\DIFERENTIAL^{2}\xi}{\DIFERENTIAL\tau^{2}}=R\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX i\COVARIANTINDEX{0j0}\xi\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX j
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the oscillating curvature tensor from a passing wave 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX i\COVARIANTINDEX{0j0}=\frac{1}{2}h^{\PARENTHESES{TF?}}\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX i\COVARIANTINDEX{j,00}
\]

\end_inset

 with initially 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX j\PARENTHESES 0=$
\end_inset

 something with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 that my eyes cannot see.
 Somehow this will induce a tidal force between the two neighboring particles
 and so the total force will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{\text{total}}=F_{\text{gravitational wave}}+F_{\text{others}}\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Detection of gravitational waves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See slides.
 We can rewrite 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Equation: sa7td89gasdoasgyou"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{h}{2}=\frac{c\Delta t}{L}
\]

\end_inset

 and here we identify 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\Delta t}{L}=\frac{\Delta L}{L}
\]

\end_inset

 and from theory we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{h}{2}\sim10^{-21}
\]

\end_inset

 and so we see that this problem is really complicated, and we can estimate
 how to build our detectors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
07.10.2021
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Gravitational wave sources
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In principle everything is a source, but we will consider only sources that
 can produce waves detectable by detectors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Binary systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is usually a last problem in a GR course.
 There are two point masses of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 both which are orbiting.
 As a result of gravitational radiation the energy is lost and the distance
 between the particles gets smaller, this increases 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, this increases the radiation (i.e.
 the amplitude), and so on.
 In reality the point masses are not point and at some point they collide
 and become one single mass.
 The results are summarized in the slides.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Binary pulsars
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With pulsars we can see at the period shift.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "here"
target "https://www.google.com/search?q=pulsar+period+shift&client=ubuntu&hs=8dn&channel=fs&sxsrf=AOaemvLE6YV8Jd4B1_ID5JYaMl6pcmAszw:1633597052054&source=lnms&tbm=isch&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjMiPmf97fzAhUSP-wKHeD6AHAQ_AUoAXoECAEQAw&biw=1920&bih=969&dpr=1#imgrc=r_Rt-hFumJNK8M"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Black hole binaries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Emission by black holes is actually easier to model than that of neutron
 stars because there is no matter.
 The models for sources with black holes are valid for any mass, it does
 not matter.
 With neutron stars this is not the case because if you have a model for
 neutron stars of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 it may not hold for mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 because many things inside the neutron star change.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The higher frequency a black hole can emit is given by the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

quasi normal modes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 obtained by perturbating the surface of a black hole.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The peak frequency of a BNS system is lower than that of black holes.
 The reason is that the neutron stars are much bigger in size, so they 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

touch
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 before than the two black holes.
 They also have much more complicated quasi normal modes which have lower
 frequency.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are different flavors of black holes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Total mass.
 Depending on the total mass of the binary we can classify them like this:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Stellar mass BH.
 This is when 
\begin_inset Formula $3M_{\sun}<M_{BH}<100M_{\sun}$
\end_inset

.
 These are black holes formed from the decay of a star.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Intermediate mass BH.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $100M_{\sun}<M_{BH}<10^{5}M_{\sun}$
\end_inset

.
 These black holes do not form from supernova explosions.
 One mechanism for these black holes is merging of multiple black holes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Super massive BH.
 Those usually found in the center of the galaxies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Near solar mass BH.
 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{BH}<3M_{\sun}$
\end_inset

.
 These have not been observed yet.
 It would be a break through for dark matter.
 There is a minimum mass for black holes given by Hawking radiation, it
 it is smaller they would have already evaporate.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The astrophysical sources of gravitational waves by binary black holes are
 intermediate mass black holes.
 This usually happens in the center of galaxies: The density of objects
 is bigger and also older so stars have already converted into black holes
 and black holes have already merged.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The higher the mass, the lower the peak frequency.
 Even if this may appear counter intuitive, the reason is that if there
 is more mass then the surface of the black hole is bigger and so the quasi
 normal modes (oscillations of its surface) have longer wavelength so lower
 frequency.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Supernovae 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The explosion of a star is not spherically symmetric (because the star rotates,
 and other effects) and because it is a very energetic process, it can emit
 gravitational waves detectable.
 The issue is that there is not a model for this type of wave basically
 because a supernova is a mess.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The detection of gravitational waves from supernovae (or neutrinos) is very
 important to understand what kind of object is left after such an event.
 The reason is that gravitational waves (and neutrinos) travel directly
 towards us without interactions, so it is a clean signal of what has happened.
 Light, which is what we use now to observe these events, scatters a lot
 with the matter of the dying star so it is very distorted.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Rotating neutron stars
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rotating neutron stars emit very weak but continuous signals.
 If you take data for many time (say 10 years) you can integrate the power
 of this signal over all your period.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
htmltag{tag_name=image}{src=https://astrobites.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/non
axisymmetric_neutron_star_sketch_lowres1.gif}{style=max-width: 100
\backslash
%;}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Emission of gravitational waves by a rotating neutron star.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Stochastic background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This signal is supposed to be constantly present, though it has not a fixed
 frequency (like rotating neutron stars) but rather a continuous spectrum.
 This is like the CMB background.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can classify this background into two categories:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Population of point sources.
 This means that there are many events that happened in the history of the
 universe, and we see all of them superimposed.
 Analogy: the noise that the drops of water produce when it rains; you listen
 a continuous noise and not the individual events.
 This is expected to be between 
\begin_inset Formula $10\UNIT{Hz}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $4\KILO{Hz}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Cosmological.
 The anisotropies observed in the CMB are related with differences in the
 density of energy.
 This must have produced somehow a gravitational wave background similar
 to the CMB.
 Because this background is very red shifted, the peak frequency is very
 low to be observed nowadays.
 There are other models which propose a very high frequency despite the
 red shift.
 We really don't know yet.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
14.10.2021
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Source modeling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Everything from today was taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Jolien Gravitational Wave Physics and Astronomy BOOK"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 chapter 3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to see the modeling of sources in a Newtonian limit.
 The non-Newtonian limit is very cumbersome.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have seen that if there is a rigid body with some extension in space,
 then we can measure a gravitational wave by measuring the heat that it
 will produce due to friction in this body.
 Gravitational waves have no energy locally (?).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a gravitational wave we consider a metric of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}=\eta\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}+h\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}=\eta\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}+\nu h^{\PARENTHESES 1}\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}+\nu^{2}h^{\PARENTHESES 2}\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}+\dots
\]

\end_inset

 This allows us to compute the Einstein tensor as a series 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
G\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu} & =R\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}-\frac{1}{2}g\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}R\\
 & =\GUNDERBRACE{G\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}}{=0}+G^{\PARENTHESES 1}\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}+G^{\PARENTHESES 2}\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}+\dots
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 EFE (Einstein Field Equation?) in vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}=0\Rightarrow0\approx\nu G^{\PARENTHESES 1}\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}\PARENTHESES{h^{\PARENTHESES 1}\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}}+\GUNDERBRACE{\nu^{2}\SQBRACKETS{G^{\PARENTHESES 2}\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}\PARENTHESES{h^{\PARENTHESES 1}\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}}+G^{\PARENTHESES 1}\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}\PARENTHESES{h^{\PARENTHESES 2}\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}}}}{=0}
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\ORDER{h^{2}}$
\end_inset

: effective stress-energy tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

 this is the source term for 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{\PARENTHESES 2}\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}$
\end_inset

 contributions.
 I think that now we replace this back into the Einstein equation to find
