\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gravitational radiation luminosity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Jolien Gravitational Wave Physics and Astronomy BOOK"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ¬ß 3.3.2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The gravitational flux is the amount of energy carried by a gravitational
 wave that crosses a spherical surface element surrounding the source per
 unit time.
 It is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\DIFERENTIAL E}{\DIFERENTIAL t\DIFERENTIAL A} & =T^{\text{GW}}\COVARIANTINDEX{03}\\
 & \vdots
\end{align*}

\end_inset

As a result we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{\text{GW}}=-\frac{\DIFERENTIAL E}{\DIFERENTIAL t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Emission by an orbiting binary system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Jolien Gravitational Wave Physics and Astronomy BOOK"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ¬ß 3.5.
 We want to compute the quadrupolar moment 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{ij}=\intop\DIFERENTIAL^{3}x\PARENTHESES{x\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX ix\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX j-\frac{r^{2}}{3}\delta\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{ij}}\rho\PARENTHESES{t,\VECTOR x}
\]

\end_inset

 Now we go to the reduced mass problem 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\LBRACE{\begin{aligned} & a=r_{1}+r_{2}\\
 & M=m_{1}+m_{2}\\
 & \mu=\frac{m_{1}m_{2}}{M}
\end{aligned}
}
\]

\end_inset

 Using this we get the expressions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Jolien Gravitational Wave Physics and Astronomy BOOK"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (3.165).
 This is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\LBRACE{\begin{aligned} & I_{11}=\frac{\mu a^{2}}{2}\PARENTHESES{1+\cos\PARENTHESES{2\varphi}}\\
 & I\COVARIANTINDEX{22}=\frac{\mu a^{2}}{2}\PARENTHESES{1-\cos\PARENTHESES{2\varphi}}\\
 & I\COVARIANTINDEX{12}=\frac{\mu a^{2}}{2}\sin\PARENTHESES{2\varphi}
\end{aligned}
}
\]

\end_inset

 Now we want to calculate the perturbation to the metric, this is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h^{TT}\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}\sim\frac{2G}{c^{4}r}\ddot{I}^{TT}\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}\PARENTHESES{t-\frac{r}{c}}
\]

\end_inset

 Replacing the previous components we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h^{TT}\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}=-\frac{4G\mu a^{2}\omega^{2}}{c^{4}r}\SQBRACKETS{\begin{matrix}\cos2\varphi & \sin2\varphi & 0\\
\sin2\varphi & -\cos2\varphi & 0\\
0 & 0 & 0
\end{matrix}}
\]

\end_inset

 We have used in the beginning that the observer is in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR z$
\end_inset

 direction, thus we already have the 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 in the TT gauge.
 If we use the polarization tensors 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\LBRACE{\begin{aligned} & \VECTOR e_{+}=\SQBRACKETS{\begin{matrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & -1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 0
\end{matrix}}\\
 & \VECTOR e_{\times}=\SQBRACKETS{\begin{matrix}0 & 1 & 0\\
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 0
\end{matrix}}
\end{aligned}
}
\]

\end_inset

then each component has amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\LBRACE{\begin{aligned} & h_{+}=-\frac{4G\mu a^{2}\omega^{2}}{c^{4}r}\cos2\varphi\\
 & h_{\times}=-\frac{4G\mu a^{2}\omega^{2}}{c^{4}r}\sin2\varphi
\end{aligned}
}
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we note that the frequency of the gravitational wave is twice the frequency
 of the orbital motion: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{\text{gravitational wave}}=2f_{\text{orbital motion}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we use 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\DEF a\omega
\]

\end_inset

 which is basically the velocity of the reduced mass orbiting body, or similar,
 then we can rewrite 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\LBRACE{\begin{aligned} & h_{+}=-\frac{4G\mu}{c^{2}r}\PARENTHESES{\frac{v}{c}}^{2}\cos2\varphi\\
 & h_{\times}=-\frac{4G\mu}{c^{2}r}\PARENTHESES{\frac{v}{c}}^{2}\sin2\varphi
\end{aligned}
}
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the observer is not exactly at 
\begin_inset Formula $\VERSOR z$
\end_inset

 but at an angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota$
\end_inset

 (iota) the amplitudes are modified according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Jolien Gravitational Wave Physics and Astronomy BOOK"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 eq.
 (3.172).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we want to see how this system evolves in time.
 Basically the gravitational radiation will carry energy, this will make
 the orbits to reduce, frequency increase and so on.
 To study this we need the gravitational wave luminosity, and for this we
 compute the third time derivative of the quadrupole tensor.
 The result is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
L_{\text{gravitational wave}} & =\frac{1}{5}\frac{G}{c^{5}}\ANGLEBRACKETS{\PARENTHESES{\ddddot{I}\COVARIANTINDEX{11}}^{2}+\PARENTHESES{\dddot{I}\COVARIANTINDEX{22}}^{2}+2\PARENTHESES{\dddot{I}\COVARIANTINDEX{12}}^{2}}\\
 & =\frac{32}{5}\frac{c^{5}}{G}\eta^{2}\PARENTHESES{\frac{v}{c}}^{10}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\DEF\frac{m_{1}m_{2}}{M^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Now we can compute the energy using 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{\text{GW}}=-\frac{\DIFERENTIAL E}{\DIFERENTIAL t}
\]

\end_inset

 and we use the Newtonian approximation for the energy 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E & =\frac{m_{2}}{2}v_{1}^{2}+\frac{m_{2}}{2}v_{2}^{2}-\frac{Gm_{1}m_{2}}{a}\\
 & \,\vdots\\
 & =-\frac{\mu}{2}v^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 Combining these two expressions we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\DIFERENTIAL\PARENTHESES{\frac{v}{c}}}{\DIFERENTIAL t}=\frac{32\eta}{5}\frac{c^{3}}{GM}\PARENTHESES{\frac{v}{c}}^{9}
\]

\end_inset

 Because we are using the Newtonian approximation, this is an approximation...
 But in the early moments of the merge we can use this formulas, i.e.
 when the two masses are enough far away from each other.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use this result to calculate the 
\emph on
time until coalescence
\emph default
.
 See in the book 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Jolien Gravitational Wave Physics and Astronomy BOOK"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for details.
 Don't know how accurate this is because the coalescence happens when the
 Newtonian approximation is not valid anymore.
 But this may happen for a short time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also calculate the phase evolution.
 Because the gravitational wave is not monochromatic (because of the decay
 of the orbital motion) the phase will not be exactly a linear function
 increasing with time.
 The details of the calculation can be seen in the book.
 Basically with this we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\varphi\PARENTHESES v$
\end_inset

 and in the end 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos2\varphi\to\cos2\varphi\PARENTHESES v$
\end_inset

.
 Again, this is Newtonian so it is an approximation.
 In the post-Newtonian case the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

 are replaced by more complicated post-Newtonian expressions and the calculation
s are done numerically.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The post-Newtonian approximations, which are gradually getting better as
 the number of terms is increased, are used as ansatz.
 The merge of the two bodies is only modeled by full GR, and to get the
 wave forms for this you have to numerically solve full GR.
 But this is very expensive computationally, so you use post-Newtonian approxima
tions which are very cheap as ansatz and then you solve the full GR.
 
\end_layout

