28.10.2021
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Gravitational wave observation and inference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What we are discussing today is in hand-written notes, not specifically
 taken from anywhere.
 If it helps, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Jolien Gravitational Wave Physics and Astronomy BOOK"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 chapter 7 has some stuff on this topics.
 I don't know how much it is related to this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Classification of data analyses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can calssify like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Utility based
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The following analyses types are in some way sequential, in the sense that
 if you fail in answering 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

is there a GW here?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 then all the other analyses cannot be performed, and so on.
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Detection of the gravitational waves within some data.
 Basically you want to say 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

yes, there is a GW
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no, there is not
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Source classification and/or parameter estimation.
 Once you have found a GW, you want to characterize the source.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Others:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Test the underlying theory (GR).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Test astrophysical formation channels.
 We use the parameters we have estimated before in conjunction with a population
 of events, to test how were these objects formed.
 Basically you can test the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cross section
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of each type of source based on the rate you observe.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Source based classification.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Transients: You catch a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

short
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 transient while your detector is on for a long time.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\text{signal}}<t_{\text{observation}}$
\end_inset

.
 Usually we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\LBRACE{\begin{aligned} & t_{\text{observation}}\sim100\text{ to }200\text{ days}\\
 & t_{\text{signal}}\sim1\MILI s\text{ to few days}
\end{aligned}
}
\]

\end_inset

 What we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\text{signal}}$
\end_inset

 is, of course, the time the signal is above the noise floor.
 The sources that produce these signals are CBC, binaries (BH-BH, NS-NS,
 BH-NS).
 Other sources are core collapse, SN, NS glitches, cosmic strings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Persistent: This is when 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\text{signal}}>t_{\text{observation}}$
\end_inset

.
 Here we can have two types of signals:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Continuous wave.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Rotating NS.
 When NS rotate they loose the spherical symmetry, and this can excite a
 number of modes that emit GW.
 The frequency of the GW is twice the frequency of rotation of the NS.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
X-ray binaries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Also NS-NS binaries in an early state.
 (Also BH-BH and BH-NS, but NS-NS binaries are known better from the electromagn
etic spectrum so they are more studied.)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Stochastic background.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Astrophysical background.
 When you have many many events happening simultaneously, you see the signals
 all mixed.
 As you look farther in space, the crust of volume at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 becomes bigger and bigger and so it contains more and more events with
 decreasing amplitude (because they are further away) but so they mix.
 So here you have an ensemble of transient sources.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cosmological background.
 This is the analogous signal to the CMB, they are primordial GW.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Methodology based.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Un-modeled methods.
 Rely on the understanding of the detectors.
 You take the data and you know your detector, so you try to see if there
 is any kind of signal, without worrying too much about which source produced
 it.
 The optimal way of doing this is to try to correlate the same signal in
 different detectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Modeled methods.
 Rely on the understanding of the source, and you try to find such signal
 in your data.
 The best way of doing this is to do model-matching to the signals.
 You can also use machine learning.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Overhead concept
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's recap the response of a GW signal in an interferometer.
 A source at position 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\phi$
\end_inset

 in the sky, and a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is producing the GW with components 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{+}\PARENTHESES t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\times}\PARENTHESES t$
\end_inset

.
 So if we have many detectors and we index them with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\EVALUATEDAT{\frac{\Delta L}{L}}k{}=F_{+}\PARENTHESES{\theta,\phi,\psi}h_{+}\PARENTHESES t+F_{\times}\PARENTHESES{\theta,\phi,\psi}h_{\times}\PARENTHESES t
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 I don't know what it is, and the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 in principle depend on time because Earth is rotating, but if we look at
 short signals (a few seconds) we can neglect this dependence.
 This may be explained in more detail in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Jolien Gravitational Wave Physics and Astronomy BOOK"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ¬ß 6.1.10.
 The response of the detector can be modeled as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\LBRACE{\begin{aligned} & F_{+}=?\\
 & F_{\times}=\frac{1}{2}\PARENTHESES{1+\cos^{2}\theta}\cos^{2}\phi\sin2\psi+\cos\theta\sin2\phi\cos2\psi
\end{aligned}
}
\]

\end_inset

 Now we define the 
\begin_inset Formula $\SNR$
\end_inset

 squared: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho^{2} & \equiv\SNR^{2}\\
 & =4\intop_{0}^{\infty}\frac{\MODULE{\frac{\Delta L}{L}\PARENTHESES f}}{S_{h}\PARENTHESES f}\DIFERENTIAL f
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the frequency, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\Delta L}{L}\PARENTHESES f$
\end_inset

 is the Fourier transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\Delta L}{L}\PARENTHESES t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{h}\PARENTHESES f$
\end_inset

 is the power spectral density.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Network of detectors 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we have a network of detectors, the effective 
\begin_inset Formula $\SNR$
\end_inset

 is improved ass 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\SNR_{\text{effective}}^{2}=\sum_{k\in\text{Detectors}}\SNR_{k}^{2}
\]

\end_inset

 where we are assuming that the detectors are independent in all sense except
 for the signal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The antenna pattern power is combined like this 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\PARENTHESES{\theta,\phi}=\sum_{k\in\text{Detectors}}F_{+,k}^{2}+F_{\times,k}^{2}
\]

\end_inset

 where we can define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{k}\PARENTHESES{\theta,\phi}\equiv F_{+,k}^{2}+F_{\times,k}^{2}
\]

\end_inset

 As you add detectors to the network, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 gets more uniform.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In real life the angle between the two arms of an interferometer are not
 exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $90\UNIT{deg}$
\end_inset

 because of technological constraints, geography, etc.
 So if this angle is 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 then we will have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\LBRACE{\begin{aligned} & F_{+}=\sin\eta\SQBRACKETS{a\cos^{2}\psi+b\sin^{2}\psi}\\
 & F_{\times}=\sin\eta\SQBRACKETS{a\cos^{2}\psi-b\sin^{2}\psi}
\end{aligned}
}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 have complicated expressions, see the notes of the professor.
 The coordinates are 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta,\lambda$
\end_inset

 the longitude and latitude of the detector, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\phi$
\end_inset

 the position of the source of GW.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Coincident and coherent formalism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have a set of signals 
\begin_inset Formula $h\PARENTHESES t$
\end_inset

 coming from each detector in the network, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{L}\PARENTHESES t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{H}\PARENTHESES t$
\end_inset

 from Ligo, 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{V}\PARENTHESES t$
\end_inset

 from Virgo, and so on.
 How do we combine all these signals to see if there is something going
 on? We can use 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Coincident formalism.
 Basically you look for time coincidences in each 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 We know GW go at the speed of light, we know the distance between each
 detector, we can compute a set of time windows withing the signals should
 be correlated if the are from the same event.
 Then we can look for such signals in all possible time windows in each
 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 If we find something with a 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\SNR=\sqrt{\sum_{k}\SNR_{k}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

 bigger than some value, we claim we have an event.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Coherent formalism.
 Here we not only use time coincidence but also two other things: The sky
 direction and the polarization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Transient detection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How do we know that we have seen a GW transient? There are glitches that
 are of course not GW events but they look like GW events.
 To estimate the occurrence of these glitches (e.g.
 earthquakes, a car crash, etc) what you do is to shift your data from each
 detector with an exagerated 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 such that the correlation between GW events is broken, and then you run
 your analyses algorithms.
 In this way you can estimate how often do glitches that look like GW happen
 in your array of detectors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So suppose we have two 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 signals from two detectors.
 We run our analysis algorithm and we find an event with some 
\begin_inset Formula $\SNR_{\text{candidate event}}$
\end_inset

.
 What is the chance that this was a random glitch and what is the chance
 it is an actual GW.
 What we do to measure the chance a totally random glitch will produce such
 an event is to shift one of the 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 in, say, 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 minutes (enough to break correlation of GW events) and then run the analysis
 algorithm.
 Then we repeat this for 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 minutes, and for 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 minutes, and so on.
 In this way we produce many thousands of years of backgrand based in real
 data which we are completely sure it has no GW events, so here each event
 we detect with the same 
\begin_inset Formula $\SNR$
\end_inset

 is a fake event.
 With this we know how often our candidate event can be produced by a random
 glitch, say we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

 glitches in 
\begin_inset Formula $100000$
\end_inset

 years of background, then we would expect to see our 
\begin_inset Formula $\SNR_{\text{candidate event}}$
\end_inset

 once every 10000 years due to random glitches.
 With this we can compute the significance of the event for each value of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\SNR$
\end_inset

.
 The lower the 
\begin_inset Formula $\SNR$
\end_inset

 the lower the significance.
 With this we can define the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

false alarm probability
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{FAP}=1-\exp\PARENTHESES{-\frac{t_{\text{observation}}}{i\text{FAR}?}}
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

