\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
11.11.2021
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Recap from the lecture I missed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Transient detection:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Unmodeled search (geometric formalism).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Modeled search.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection*
Modeled methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this you need a signal that you can fit with a model.
 Thus, such signal must be somehow 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

happening all the time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To perform a modeled search we need:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Template bank.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Likelihood (SNR).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consistency checking (detection statistics).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Template bank
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A bank of waveform models.
 These models should cover all the parameter space you want to explore (mass,
 spin, etc).
 You also need to know the power spectral density of your detector (to know
 how probable is that what you have fitted is a signal or just noise).
 The parameters space is discretized to produce the template bank, otherwise
 it would be infinite.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Parameter space.
 If we are looking for signals produced by binaries, our parameters space
 is composed by the two masses 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1},m_{2}$
\end_inset

, the 3 spin components of each mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\VECTOR s_{1},\VECTOR s_{2}$
\end_inset

, the eccentricity of the orbit which is one number.
 There can be other parameters depending on the model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The majority of the mergers happen with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

parallel spins
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\VECTOR s_{1}\parallel\VECTOR s_{2}\parallel\VECTOR L_{\text{Orbital}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Eccentricity is usually 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The mass can be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

anything
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Usually we consider one of them to be 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\text{high}}$
\end_inset

 and the other one to be 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\text{low}}$
\end_inset

.
 Typical values for 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\text{high}}\sim100M_{\sun}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\text{low}}\sim1M_{\sun}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
We have to define how we will discretize the parameters space.
 Suppose we have two values of the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\BRACES{m_{1},m_{2},\VECTOR s_{1},\VECTOR s_{2},\dots}$
\end_inset

).
 With these parameters we produce two waveforms 
\begin_inset Formula $h\PARENTHESES{\theta_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\PARENTHESES{\theta_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 We need a way of measuring the distance from 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{2}$
\end_inset

 in order to know how to properly discretize the parameters space.
 There are many fancy ways of doing this, here we will define the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

match
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu & =\PARENTHESES{\frac{h\PARENTHESES{\theta_{1}}}{\MODULE{\MODULE{h\PARENTHESES{\theta_{1}}}}}|\frac{h\PARENTHESES{\theta_{2}}}{\MODULE{\MODULE{h\PARENTHESES{\theta_{2}}}}}}\\
 & =4\REALPART{\intop_{f_{\text{low}}}^{f_{\text{high}}}\frac{\tilde{h}\PARENTHESES{\theta_{1}}\tilde{h}\PARENTHESES{\theta_{2}}}{\tilde{S}_{n}\PARENTHESES f}\DIFERENTIAL f}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}_{n}\PARENTHESES f$
\end_inset

 is the PSD and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{h}$
\end_inset

 are probably the Fourier transforms.
 This quantity is measuring how much SNR you looks if you use 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 For example 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0.9$
\end_inset

 tells that you loose 
\begin_inset Formula $10\UNIT{\%}$
\end_inset

 of SNR.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I think this is explained in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Jolien Gravitational Wave Physics and Astronomy BOOK"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ¬ß 7.2.2, or nearby.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Likelihood (SNR)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Look at 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reference: Jolien Gravitational Wave Physics and Astronomy BOOK"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ¬ß 7.2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our data 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\PARENTHESES t=n\PARENTHESES t+s\PARENTHESES t
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is noise and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is signal.
 We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is Gaussian with mean 0.
\end_layout

