\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gravitational wave
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each stage is calculated in a different way, the most complicated is the
 plunge and merger stages where numerical relativity has to be used.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Numerical relativity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 1952 it was probed that the EFE in vacuum are well posed, i.e.
 that there is solution and that small changes in initial conditions produce
 small changes in solutions so this is stable and continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The EFE are 10 quasi-linear wave-like equations with hyperbolic stability
 properties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 1962, 1972 it was introduced the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ADM formalism
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which looks into the Cauchy problem for PDEs and then formulates the EFE
 as a computable and iterable process in time steps that go from the initial
 state to the final state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
ADM formalism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3+1 decompositions (3-dim space like slices with fixed coordinate times.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
htmltag{tag_name=image}{src=https://www.frontiersin.org/files/Articles/536296/fspa
s-07-00058-HTML/image_m/fspas-07-00058-g001.jpg}{style=max-width: 100
\backslash
%;}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
ADM formalism.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 4 dimensions the interval is, as we know, 
\begin_inset Formula $\DIFERENTIAL s^{2}=g\COVARIANTINDEX{\mu\nu}\DIFERENTIAL x\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\mu}\DIFERENTIAL x\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 In 3+1 formalism this is written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\DIFERENTIAL s^{2}=-\alpha^{2}\DIFERENTIAL t^{2}+\gamma\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}\PARENTHESES{\DIFERENTIAL x\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX i+\beta\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX i\DIFERENTIAL t}\PARENTHESES{\DIFERENTIAL x\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX j+\beta\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX i\DIFERENTIAL t}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\CONTRAVARIANTINDEX{ij}$
\end_inset

 are 3 dimensions metrics and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta\COVARIANTINDEX i$
\end_inset

 are gauge variables.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lapse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and measures the rate in proper time progression between two slices of
 spacetime while 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\COVARIANTINDEX i$
\end_inset

 is sthe shift vector and measures the change of spacial coordinates between
 different slices.
 See the previous figure.
 The lapse 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 has to be chosen in order to avoid singularities, improve convergence and
 speed up the simulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is also an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

extrinsic curvature tensor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $K\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}$
\end_inset

 that separates the intrinsic curvature of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}$
\end_inset

 from the extrinsic one.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the EFE we have 6 evolution equations + 4 constraint equations.
 In the ADM formalism look 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "here"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ADM_formalism"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, there are 3 equations of motion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}$
\end_inset

 and 3 for 
\begin_inset Formula $K\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}$
\end_inset

 which come from the 6 evolution equations in EFE, and the 4 constraint
 equations are applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this formalism there are two types of equations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Hyperbolic, i.e.
 wave-like equations.
 These are nice because they have a rapid convergence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Parabolic, i.e.
 time-dependent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These problems are mathematically stable once initial constraints are satisfied.
 However in full GR there is a lot of non-linearity and the small numerical
 computational errors can blow up.
 This blow up due to the non-linearity is the challenge of numerical relativity.
 For this we have to keep the constraints satisfied at all times and this
 guaranties that stable and convergent solutions exist.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Suitable initial conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
BSSNOK approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is one problem which is to propose suitable initial conditions.
 This was solved during the 1990s by Baugmarde, Shapiro (1998) and Shibala,
 Nakamura (1995) in the so called BSSNOK approach.
 The problem is that we have 12 real numbers that are the initial data for
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K\COVARIANTINDEX{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 These numbers are not all independent, they are related to the parameters
 of the system, e.g.
 the mass and spin of the black holes, and the initial orbit dynamics.
 We want to know how are they related so we can solve the problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Generalized harmonic coordinates with constraint damping (GHCD)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a different approach.
 Not understanding too much.
 There are two unstable scalar field profiles: initial amplitudes, boosts,
 separaitons.
 These are chosen such that approximates two black holes in orbit.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Handling of physical singularities of black holes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is another problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Excision
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is one way of solving the singularities problem.
 We have different types of black holes, Schwarzschild and Kerr.
 Both have event horizons that shield the singularities.
 What we do is to simulate outside the event horizon if I understood correctly.
 (Unruh 1984)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are challenging boundary conditions due to irregular shape of black
 hole horizons.
 This creates numerical artifacts and in particular emission of gravitational
 waves that is unphysical.
 To mitigate this problem you have to fine tune the constraints.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Punctures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is another way of solving the singularities problem.
 This solution was introduced by Hahn, Lindquist in 1964 axisymmetric coalescenc
e of two black holes.
 Here you somehow design your space time such that the solution avoids the
 singularities using wormholes, or something similar.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This technique lead to the first successful simulation of two black holes,
 not until 2005.
 Some modifications to the original punctures approach were done, for example
 letting the punctures to freely move in the coordinates system.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Discretization and gridding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is another problem.
 In the initial problem, probably after a Newtonian ansatz, there are two
 BH well separated in a flat spacetime.
 Then you evolve the simulation and you go into coalescence where the two
 black holes are close and the space time is highly curved.
 The two situations have very different length scales so the numerical mesh
 that we take in each case has to be very different.
 We need an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

adaptive mesh refinement
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 In this field not much progress was done.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Integration procedure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is another problem.
 There are different options
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Finite difference methods (FD) which approximate the solution of the PDEs
 at specific points in the mesh.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Spectral interpolation methods (SpEC).
 Fit smooth functions to several points in the mesh.
 This produces accurate solutions at any location in the mesh.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gravitational wave extraction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another problem.
 I don't know what do we want to do now.
 They use the Newman-Penrose approach.
 They calculate the Weyl scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{4}$
\end_inset

 approximation of GW radiation at spatial infinity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Phenomenological IMR modeling in frequency domain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These are very fast because they are analytical, you don't need to solve
 any equation.
 It is done in frequency domain because of convenience.
 They combine analytical approaches from numerical relativity.
 To go to the frequency domain we use the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stationary phase approximation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
09.12.2021
