\begin_layout Subsection
Strong-field tests of GR
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we have binary pulsars.
 In 1974 it was found the first binary pulsar 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "PSR B1913+16"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hulse%E2%80%93Taylor_binary"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Because these are very dense objects, the system emits gravitational waves.
 This loss of energy reduces the orbital period, and this was measured to
 be in agreement with GR.
 This system is in a very early stage of the merge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
htmltag{tag_name=image}{src=https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0
/04/PSR_B1913
\backslash
%2B16_period_shift_graph.svg/800px-PSR_B1913
\backslash
%2B16_period_shift_graph.svg.png}{style=max-height: 90vh;}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

