\begin_layout Standard
In 2003 a 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "double pulsar system"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PSR_J0737%E2%88%923039"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was discovered.
 This also provides a good test for GR and up to now is in agreement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tests of GR with compact binary coalescence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use the gravitational wave events from LIGO and company to test GR.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can perform a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

residuals test
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which is basically to look at 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{data}-\text{model}$
\end_inset

.
 If the model is good, you will only see noise here, if there is something
 wrong in your model, you will see not just noise but a component of the
 signal that is not in the model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can also do a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

least-damped QNM
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which looks if the data is consistent with GR prediction of QNMs (quasi
 normal modes) of the remnant black hole.
 For this there is a signal model for 
\begin_inset Formula $t>t_{0}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the time at which the QNM start, and loos like 
\begin_inset Formula $h\PARENTHESES t\sim e^{-\frac{t-t_{0}}{\tau}}\cos\PARENTHESES{2\pi f_{0}\PARENTHESES{t-t_{0}}+\phi_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Waveform self-consistengy.
 There is a prediction for the waveform and it has to be consistent.
 This means that if we estimate the final mass and spin of the black hole
 after the merger in two 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

independent ways
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
using data from the inspiral stage and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
using data from the ringdown + merger stage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we want the mass and spin to be the same, independently of which of these
 regions we use.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Massive graviton? If the graviton is massive, there should be dispersion
 in the propagation of gravitational waves.
 Up to now there is on evidence for dispersion and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\text{graviton}}\le1\TIMESTENTOTHE{-22}\UNIT{eV}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Parameterized deviations from GR.
 This I think it is basically to see if other things that are not exactly
 GR fit better the data than GR does.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Difference in the speed of light and gravity.
 This is done combining data from gravitational wave and electromagnetic
 observations of the same event, and then we can compare the time of arrival
 of each.
 
\end_layout

